Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, black’s king on g8 is in check from the white rook on d8 along rank 8 (with e8 and f8 empty). Black must respond by either moving the king or blocking the check. (Note that no black piece can capture the checking rook.)

Looking at the king’s options:
• Moving to f8 or h8 would keep the king on rank 8 and still in the rook’s line.
• Moving to f7 is unsafe because the white bishop on g6 controls that diagonal (g6→f7).
• Moving to h7 is also ruled out because the bishop covers h7.
• That leaves only g7 as a safe square for the king.

Thus, the best move is to play king from g8 to g7.

make_move g8g7

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one promising idea is to activate your rook. For instance, moving your rook from b2 down to b1 (i.e. "b2b1" in UCI notation) places it on the first rank where it directly attacks White’s king positioned on g1 along that rank. In other words, after b2b1 the line from b1 through c1, d1, e1, f1 up to g1 is open, and White’s king is in check.

Before finalizing, let’s quickly check the details:
• Your rook is currently on b2 (file b, rank2). The square b1 (file b, rank1) is empty.
• Once on b1, your rook gives check along rank1 toward the White king at g1.
• The White king cannot capture the rook on b1 because it’s too far away (g1 is not adjacent to b1), and blocking the check isn’t possible except by moving the king.
• Other piece moves (such as pawn advances or a king move) don’t create an immediate threat as forceful as this checking move.

With these considerations, the move "b2b1" looks very appealing.

make_move b2b1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board (FEN: 8/8/1R5p/5k2/p3pp2/8/8/6K1 b - - 7 74), Black’s pieces are:

• Black King on f5  
• Black Pawns on a4, e4, f4, and h6

It’s Black’s turn. The white rook on b6 controls the entire 6th rank (all the way from a6 to g6), so any king move into rank 6 (such as f5→f6, f5→g6, or f5→e6) would be moving into check.

Examining the king’s legal moves from f5 (its eight adjacent squares):
 – f6: Illegal (attacked by Rook on b6)  
 – g6: Illegal (attacked by Rook on b6)  
 – e6: Illegal (attacked by Rook on b6)  
 – f4: Occupied by your pawn on f4  
 – e4: Occupied by your pawn on e4  
 – e5: Legal, but note that it does not help defend your pawn on h6 which is also on an attack line from the white rook.  
 – g5: Legal and importantly, from g5 your king will be adjacent to the pawn on h6 (adjacent squares around h6 include g5, g6, and h5), thus defending it.  
 – g4: Legal but does not help guard h6.

Since the pawn on h6 is currently directly attacked by the white rook along the 6th rank, it is crucial to defend it. Moving your king to g5 accomplishes that while keeping your king safe from checks by the rook.

Therefore, I’ll choose the move:

make_move f5g5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, I notice the following key points:

• White’s pieces are the king on e1 and a rook on d8. The rook, from d8, controls the entire d‐file (d1–d7) as well as the 8th rank.

• Black’s pieces are the king on c3 and four pawns on a4, e4, f4, and h6. Since Black’s pawns move “down” (toward rank 1), it’s important to improve king activity to support their advance while avoiding white rook checks along the d–file.

• In this position, Black’s king on c3 has several legal moves. However, any move onto the d–file (i.e. d2, d3, or d4) would drop the king into the rook’s line of fire. Out of the safe options (b2, b3, b4, c2, or c4), moving the king to b3 seems most attractive. It both improves king activity and moves it slightly away from the d–file while still staying near Black’s pawns (for example, the a–pawn might become a passed candidate with king support).

Therefore, I choose to play the king to b3. In UCI format, that move is:

make_move c3b3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, I see our only major piece is the king on c6 (the black king) along with three pawns. Both white rooks (one on b8 and one on e5) are very active, and one of white’s pawns is guarding h5 while the white king sits on h3. To evade the long-range batteries of the rooks, I want our king to step off any potentially dangerous lines while staying centralized. One candidate is moving our king from c6 to d6. That move avoids the b‑file that the rook on b8 commands (so we aren’t venturing onto b7 or b6, which are unsafe) and also keeps us off Rank 5 (which is completely ruled by the rook on e5). 

Thus, after analyzing the safe adjacent squares, I decide on the move:

make_move c6d6

I’ll now play c6d6 as my move.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one of Black’s pawns is on g2 (the only pawn that isn’t blocked) and it’s just one step from the promotion rank. (Recall that—in standard algebraic notation for Black—pawns advance “down” so that a pawn on g2 reaches g1 and promotes.) However, if we promote to a queen (or rook or bishop), the new piece will immediately stand on g1 along the first rank – which is in line with the White rook on c1. That rook would then be able to immediately capture the promoted piece along rank 1.

To minimize the material loss, Black’s best try is to underpromote to a knight. With a knight on g1 the move produces an immediate check, and since a knight is valued lower (roughly 3 points) than a queen (9 points), if White chooses to capture it the exchange is less devastating. (In fact, from g1 a knight attacks f3, h3, and e2; notably, h3 is exactly where White’s king sits.) 

Thus, the move we choose is to push the pawn from g2 to g1 and underpromote to a knight—that is, we play:

  make_move g2g1n

This move gives check and forces White to respond immediately, hopefully limiting White’s immediate recapture options.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board provided, the only Black pieces are the king on e5 and two pawns (one on h6 and one on f4). (Recall that for Black, pawns move “forward” downward, toward lower ranks.) Neither pawn can move—h6’s forward square (h5) is occupied by a white pawn, and f4’s forward square (f3) is blocked by a white pawn, with no available diagonal captures for either.

That leaves Black’s king on e5. Its normally available one‐step moves from e5 would be to:
 • d6, e6, f6 (the three forward/up diagonal and vertical moves)
 • d5 and f5 (to the sides)
 • d4 and e4 (to the rear diagonally and directly) 
 • (f4 is illegal since a Black pawn occupies that square)

However, note that the white pawn on f3 attacks e4 (and g4), so e4 is off‐limits. This leaves these legal king moves:
 d6, e6, f6, d5, f5, and d4.

Choosing a safe and active square is important. In this position, moving the king to f6 (from e5 to f6 in UCI notation “e5f6”) appears natural. It centralizes the king without stepping into any opponent “attacks” (remembering that the white pawn on h5 attacks g6 and the white pawn on f3 covers e4 and g4, which do not affect f6) and avoids getting too close to the white king on h3.

Therefore, my move as Black is:

make_move e5f6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, here’s a quick analysis:

• Black’s pieces are the king on e6 and two pawns – one on f4 and one on h6.  
• The pawn on f4 cannot move forward (f3 is blocked by an enemy pawn) nor capture, and the pawn on h6 is blocked by the white pawn on h5 (with no capture available diagonally).  
• That leaves only the black king. From e6 the king can in theory move to any adjacent square: d7, e7, f7, d6, f6, d5, e5, or f5.  
• However, the white rook on c7 (sitting on rank 7) controls the entire 7th rank. Thus, moving to d7, e7, or f7 would place the king in check.  
• The safe king moves are then d6, f6, d5, e5, or f5.

A reasonable choice is to move toward the kingside, and so we can play King from e6 to f6.

I'll now make the move:

make_move e6f6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the diagram, here’s how I interpret the board (using standard algebraic coordinates with rank 8 at the top and rank 1 at the bottom):

• Rank 8: a8 = ♖ (white rook), the rest are empty.
• Rank 7: g7 = ♚ (black king)
• Rank 6: h6 = ♟ (black pawn)
• Rank 5: h5 = ♙ (white pawn)
• Rank 4: f4 = ♟ (black pawn) and g4 = ♔ (white king)
• Rank 3: a3 = ♖ (white rook) and f3 = ♙ (white pawn)
• The remaining squares are empty.

It appears black’s available material is the king on g7 and two pawns (on f4 and h6). None of the pawns can move forward (both are blocked by enemy pieces directly in front, and their diagonal target squares are empty since no enemy piece sits there). That leaves the black king as the piece with mobility.

Let’s consider the king’s potential moves from g7. Its surrounding squares (in algebraic form) are:
 • f6, g6, h6, f7, h7, f8, g8, h8.
However, note the following:
 – h6 is occupied by our own pawn.
 – f8, g8, and h8 lie along rank 8 and are attacked by the white rook on a8.
 – g6 is controlled by the white pawn on h5 (since from h5 white’s pawn captures diagonally forward onto g6).
That leaves f6, f7, and h7. Among these, f7 is a solid choice: it keeps the king centrally placed without stepping into any line of fire from the white pieces.

Thus, I will make the move  g7 to f7, which in UCI notation is:

make_move g7f7

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, Black’s only pieces are the king on e7 and two pawns (on f4 and h6), but both pawns are stuck (their forward squares are occupied by White’s pieces). That leaves us only with king moves. For the king on e7 the adjacent squares are:
 • Up-left: d8
 • Up: e8
 • Up-right: f8
 • Left: d7
 • Right: f7
 • Down-left: d6
 • Down: e6
 • Down-right: f6

However, note that the white rook on a6 controls the entire sixth rank (since the line a6–b6–...–g6 is open), so moving the king onto any square on rank 6 (d6, e6, f6) would put it into check.

Among the safe squares, one reasonable choice is to move the king to d8. This sidesteps the rank where the white rook on a6 is active and avoids the file of the white rook on g1. Therefore, I will play:

make_move e7d8

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Player_Black (to Proxy):

It appears that Black’s king on b8 is currently in check from White’s queen on d8 along the 8th rank. (Looking at the FEN "1k1Qr3/ppp1Ppp1/6b1/4P3/P5PP/1NP5/2P2KB1/R7", the white queen on d8 has a clear horizontal line to b8 since the square c8 is empty.) 

Since none of the king’s adjacent squares are available (or safe) and no other piece can interpose on the only blocking square (c8), the only legal way to get out of check is to capture the checking queen.

Black’s rook on e8 is in a perfect position to do just that:
 • Moving the rook from e8 to d8 (uci: "e8d8") captures the queen and, in doing so, removes the check. 

Thus, my legal move is:

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one immediate tactical concern is White’s knight on d5, which has a tempting jump to c7 that would fork your king on e8 and your rook on a8. To avoid this, one solid idea is to remove the rook from the a8 square so that when White’s knight goes to c7 (if it chooses to), it can’t fork both the king and a major piece.

A good prophylactic move is to shift your rook from a8 to b8. This move keeps your rook active along the 8th rank and sidesteps the potential fork. 

make_move a8b8

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Before making my move, I want to point out a tactical nuance in the position. Notice that Black’s bishop on f8 is currently serving as an essential block: it prevents the white rook on a8 from delivering a discovered check along the 8th rank to our king on g8. In other words, moving that bishop off f8 (for example, with the attempted move f8g7) would open up the 8th rank and expose our king to a check from the white rook on a8, which is illegal.

Given that, we must keep the bishop on f8 in place. Our legal choices now include moves with our king or pawns. One safe and natural idea is to step our king from g8 to h8. With the king on h8 the bishop stays on f8 blocking the rook’s line, and our king sidesteps any potential future discovered checks that might arise if the black bishop ever moves (for instance, if we’re forced into a pawn move that loosens the situation or if later tactics force our bishop to relocate).

Thus, I will play:

make_move g8h8

Your turn!

we note a critical detail. The black bishop currently on f8 is serving as a shield: it interposes along the 8th rank between the white rook on a8 and our black king on h8. (The rook sees along the entire rank‑8: a8, b8, …, f8, g8, h8.) If we try to move the bishop – for example, from f8 to d6 – the white rook would have an open, unobstructed line to our king on h8. That would be an illegal move because it would expose our king to check.

Our options now include moves that don’t disturb that important interposition and keep our king safe. One natural idea is to make a pawn move that neither interferes with the bishop nor opens any new vulnerabilities. For instance, moving the pawn on h7 one square forward to h6 (uci: "h7h6") is a solid choice. It does not affect the bishop’s blocking duty and even creates a little “luft” (an escape square) for the king if needed later.

Thus, I choose:

  make_move h7h6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one important concern is that Black’s pawn on d5 is defended solely by the bishop on e4 (since d5 and e4 share a diagonal). Moving that bishop immediately (say to f5 or f3) would drop the defense of d5 and allow White’s knight from f4 to capture on d5—with a free pawn coming at Black’s expense.

A good plan is to shore up the defense of d5 before considering a bishop maneuver. One natural idea is to advance the pawn on c7 one square (c7–c6). Once on c6, that pawn will help protect d5 (since a pawn on c6 captures diagonally and will cover d5), ensuring that if White’s knight ever jumps in and takes on d5, Black can recapture with ...c6xd5.

This move not only secures the central pawn but also helps activate Black’s queenside majority. It’s a sound, prophylactic move that prepares for later piece re‑positioning (for example, later freeing the bishop to find a more active post without worrying about losing the d5 pawn).

I’ll now play:

make_move c7c6

Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one tactical idea comes from using the knight on e4. Notice that from e4, the knight can capture the pawn on g3 with the move e4g3. From g3 the knight immediately threatens two very valuable enemy pieces: it attacks d1 (where white’s queen sits) and h1 (the white rook). White will have difficulty saving both, and if forced to choose, black stands to win the exchange (rook for knight) or even more if white isn’t careful.

Thus, a strong candidate move is:

I’ll play  Qe3g3 —that is, moving the queen from e3 to g3. This move not only avoids the f1–d3 diagonal (so it isn’t immediately captured by White’s bishop on f1) but also puts pressure on White’s knight on h2. White must now decide how to save that knight, and in a position where Black is already overwhelmingly ahead in material, winning the knight (or provoking concessions) should only increase Black’s advantage.

Let me know if you’d like to see the available legal moves or further discussion.
